atize the notion of a seamless relationship between identity and practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aGay immigrants -- United States. 0aGay immigrantszUnited States. 0aGay peoplezLatin AmericaxIdentity. 0aGay peoplezUnited StatesxIdentity. 0aGays -- Latin America -- Identity. 0aGays -- United States -- Identity. 0aGayszLatin AmericaxIdentity. 0aGayszUnited StatesxIdentity. 0aLatin America -- Emigration and immigration -- Social aspects. 0aLatin Americans -- United States. 0aLatin AmericanszUnited States. 0aUnited States -- Emigration and immigration -- Social aspects. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Ethnography. 4aGender and Sexuality : Lesbian / Gay Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Queer Studies. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aVidal-Ortiz, Salvador, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143845336140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438453361423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438453361/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles